        ],
        'B1' => [
            ['How do you manage stress in your daily life?', 'I manage stress by exercising regularly and journaling in the evenings. When I feel overwhelmed, I take a short walk without my phone. Talking to friends also helps me keep things in perspective.', 'List 2–3 strategies + explain.', ['stress', 'overwhelmed', 'perspective', 'journal']],
            ['Do you think mental health is taken seriously enough today?', 'More than before, but still not enough. People talk about mental health more openly, which is progress. Yet many still hide their struggles because of stigma, and support services are often underfunded. We\'re moving in the right direction, but slowly.', 'Acknowledge progress + remaining gaps.', ['stigma', 'underfunded', 'support service', 'direction']],
            ['Describe a healthy habit you\'ve built and how you maintain it.', 'I\'ve built a habit of running three times a week. I keep it by scheduling runs in my calendar and not negotiating with myself. On lazy days I tell myself to just do ten minutes, which usually turns into a full run.', 'Explain the habit + maintenance strategy.', ['habit', 'schedule', 'negotiate', 'lazy']],
            ['How important is sleep for your overall well-being?', 'Hugely important. When I sleep well, I think clearly and feel positive. When I don\'t, everything feels harder. I now treat sleep as a priority, not a luxury, and protect my evenings accordingly.', 'Use contrast to show the effect.', ['priority', 'luxury', 'protect', 'accordingly']],
            ['What do you think about diets and fitness trends?', 'I\'m sceptical of extreme trends — they usually aren\'t sustainable. I believe in simple, consistent habits: eat mostly whole foods, move your body daily, and avoid anything that feels like punishment. The best plan is one you can keep for years.', 'Express scepticism + offer principles.', ['sceptical', 'sustainable', 'whole food', 'punishment']],
            ['How has your view of health changed as you\'ve grown older?', 'When I was young I took health for granted. Now I see it as something to actively maintain, like a relationship. I\'ve also learned that mental and physical health are deeply connected — neglecting one affects the other.', 'Contrast past and present understanding.', ['take for granted', 'maintain', 'connected', 'neglect']],
        ],
        'B2' => [
            ['"Prevention is better than cure." Discuss in the context of modern healthcare.', 'I strongly agree, yet modern systems often reward treatment over prevention because it\'s more profitable and measurable. Shifting to prevention means investing in education, nutrition and lifestyle — slower, less glamorous, but far cheaper in the long run. The logic is clear; the politics is hard.', 'Engage with system-level reasoning.', ['prevention', 'profitable', 'measurable', 'glamorous']],
            ['How should society address the rise in mental health issues?', 'It needs a layered response: better access to therapy, but also prevention through stronger communities and less pressure. Social media and economic insecurity are real drivers, so purely medical solutions won\'t suffice. We have to treat mental health as a public health issue, not just an individual one.', 'Argue for systemic, not just individual, solutions.', ['layered', 'therapy', 'insecurity', 'public health']],
            ['Is the wellness industry helpful or exploitative?', 'Both, unfortunately. It has normalised self-care and brought useful practices mainstream, but it also monetises anxiety with expensive products of dubious value. The line between genuine well-being and commercialised insecurity is often blurred, which makes consumers vulnerable.', 'Hold a nuanced dual view.', ['monetise', 'dubious', 'mainstream', 'vulnerable']],
            ['How might technology both help and harm our health in the future?', 'Wearables and AI diagnostics could catch disease early and personalise treatment, which is revolutionary. But constant tracking can also fuel anxiety and reduce health to data. The net effect depends on whether we design these tools to serve humans or to extract attention and profit.', 'Use a balanced conditional structure.', ['wearable', 'diagnostic', 'personalise', 'extract']],
            ['Discuss the relationship between socioeconomic status and health.', 'The relationship is stark and well-documented. Wealth buys better food, safer environments, less stress and better care, so health gaps mirror wealth gaps. Addressing this isn\'t simply a medical question — it requires tackling inequality itself, which is why progress is so slow.', 'Connect health to broader social structures.', ['stark', 'socioeconomic', 'mirror', 'tackle']],
            ['Should individuals or governments bear more responsibility for public health?', 'It has to be shared, but I lean towards greater government responsibility for the structural factors individuals can\'t control — air quality, food regulation, healthcare access. Individuals remain responsible for their choices, but those choices are shaped by the environment policy creates. Blaming individuals alone lets systems off the hook.', 'Argue for shared but structural responsibility.', ['structural', 'regulation', 'environment', 'off the hook']],
        ],
    ],

